				\begin{document}$$\gamma $$\end{document}γ is the recovery rate. The introduction of the exposed individuals (E) in the SEIR model makes the model more efficient than the SIR model. We have shown different compartments of the SEIR model in Fig. 2. In Sect. 2.1, we have discussed how the infant propagates (S-I-R) from one compartment to another. In the SEIR model, the exposed compartment is an addition to the SIR model. Transmission occurs when there is adequate contact of a susceptible with an infective. Then, the susceptible enters the exposed class (E) of those in the latent period, who are infected but not yet infectious. At the end of the latent period, the individual enters the class (I) and they are capable of transmitting the infection. After the end of the infectious period, the individual enters the class R.

